Step 1: kube-state-metrics running in EKS

👉 It creates a pod + service

Example:

kubectl get svc -n monitoring

Output:

kube-state-metrics   ClusterIP   10.x.x.x   8080

👉 This service exposes:

http://kube-state-metrics:8080/metrics
🧩 Step 2: ServiceMonitor (IMPORTANT)

👉 This is the key piece you’re missing

A ServiceMonitor tells Prometheus:

👉 “Hey! go scrape this service”

Example:

apiVersion: monitoring.coreos.com/v1
kind: ServiceMonitor
metadata:
  name: kube-state-metrics
spec:
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: kube-state-metrics
  endpoints:
  - port: http
    interval: 30s

👉 Translation:

Find service with label app=kube-state-metrics

Hit /metrics every 30 sec

🧩 Step 3: Prometheus Operator

👉 This is running in your cluster (installed via Helm)

It does:

Watches ServiceMonitor objects

Automatically updates Prometheus config

👉 You DON’T manually edit prometheus.yml

🧩 Step 4: Prometheus scrapes

Now Prometheus knows:

👉 “I need to scrape this service”

So it calls:

http://kube-state-metrics:8080/metrics

and stores data.

🔁 Full Flow in One Line

👉 Service → ServiceMonitor → Prometheus Operator → Prometheus → Metrics stored

🔥 Real-Life Analogy (easy)

Think like this:

kube-state-metrics = teacher giving data

Service = classroom address

ServiceMonitor = timetable

Prometheus = student collecting notes
